WEBVTT

00:03.210 --> 00:05.880
Meredith: When a patient is
dying on the table,

00:05.880 --> 00:08.500
the surgeon has to keep going,
no matter what.

00:08.500 --> 00:10.960
♪♪

00:10.960 --> 00:13.670
4-0 Prolene.

00:13.670 --> 00:15.830
♪♪

00:15.830 --> 00:19.460
When we have to pee,
we hold it.

00:19.460 --> 00:22.040
When we're heartbroken,
we ignore it.

00:22.040 --> 00:23.250
Helm,
hang another unit.

00:23.250 --> 00:24.380
We're out of blood.

00:24.380 --> 00:25.580
When we're having
a miscarriage

00:25.580 --> 00:29.120
and our husband
has just been shot --

00:29.120 --> 00:30.830
well, you remember.
[ Monitor beeping ]

00:30.830 --> 00:33.170
You promised me,
Dr. Grey.

00:33.170 --> 00:36.080
[ Beeping continues ]

00:36.080 --> 00:37.250
♪♪

00:37.250 --> 00:39.250
[ Monitor beeping rapidly ]

00:39.250 --> 00:40.620
The heart, Helm,
where's the heart?

00:40.620 --> 00:42.790
She doesn't know.

00:42.790 --> 00:44.420
Get me the crash cart!
Charge to 200!

00:44.420 --> 00:46.500
The hope that
we can fix this patient

00:46.500 --> 00:48.580
is what keeps us going through
the worst moments of our lives.
Clear!

00:48.580 --> 00:49.880
[ Thump ]

00:49.880 --> 00:51.250
[ Paddles whine ]

00:51.250 --> 00:52.250
Clear!
[ Thump ]

00:52.250 --> 00:54.000
[ Gasps loudly ]

00:57.960 --> 00:59.290
If you're not gonna leave,

00:59.290 --> 01:01.330
at least be quiet
so I can sleep.

01:01.330 --> 01:04.250
[ Breathing heavily ]
Sorry.

01:04.250 --> 01:06.500
I had a bad dream.

01:06.500 --> 01:08.790
How long are you planning on
doing this for?

01:08.790 --> 01:11.540
Until you talk to me.

01:13.540 --> 01:16.670
[ Hearts & Colors' "Lion"
playing ]

01:16.670 --> 01:25.580
♪♪

01:25.580 --> 01:27.670
[ Gasps ]

01:27.670 --> 01:28.920
[ Gasps ]
Whoa. Whoa, what's --

01:28.920 --> 01:30.710
[ Quietly ] Shh.
We fell asleep.

01:30.710 --> 01:32.540
♪ There's a room stretched out
in front of me ♪
[ Quietly ] So?

01:32.540 --> 01:34.080
So we've never done that.
We've never even discussed it.

01:34.080 --> 01:35.170
[ Sighs ]

01:35.170 --> 01:37.000
Discussed falling asleep?

01:37.000 --> 01:39.460
Well,
you can't leave now.

01:39.460 --> 01:40.960
Not until I make sure
the kids are gone.

01:40.960 --> 01:42.250
They just found out about
Mer and DeLuca.

01:42.250 --> 01:43.420
I'm not gonna spring
someone else on them.

01:43.420 --> 01:44.830
But I have to pee.

01:44.830 --> 01:47.040
Well, you shoulda gone
before falling asleep.

01:47.040 --> 01:48.880
♪ Still two steps back
from where I wanna be ♪
[ Door opens ]

01:48.880 --> 01:50.290
♪ There's a lion
in the wardrobe ♪

01:50.290 --> 01:51.620
[ Groans ]
♪ And a wolf at the door ♪

01:51.620 --> 01:52.880
[ Insect buzzes ]

01:52.880 --> 01:54.540
♪ I might never get to heaven ♪

01:54.540 --> 01:56.380
♪ But I've been there before ♪

01:56.380 --> 01:58.620
♪ 'Cause when she's lying
in my sheets ♪

01:58.620 --> 02:01.210
♪ In that new T-shirt I bought ♪
[ Breathes deeply ]

02:01.210 --> 02:03.040
♪ Ain't no place
that I gotta be ♪

02:03.040 --> 02:04.790
♪ Still two steps back
from where I wanna be ♪

02:04.790 --> 02:06.670
[ Sighs ]

02:06.670 --> 02:09.000
♪♪

02:09.000 --> 02:10.169
[ Zipper unzips ]

02:10.169 --> 02:11.790
Hey.

02:11.790 --> 02:13.580
How you feeling?

02:13.580 --> 02:14.710
Mm.

02:14.710 --> 02:17.290
[ Inhales deeply ]

02:17.290 --> 02:20.460
I think I'm, um --
What's the word?

02:20.460 --> 02:22.000
Rested?

02:22.000 --> 02:23.330
Mm-hmm.

02:23.330 --> 02:24.670
[ Chuckles ]

02:24.670 --> 02:26.120
♪ 'Cause you hop on the train
like a vagabond ♪

02:26.120 --> 02:27.580
You know
you can say it.

02:27.580 --> 02:31.420
You can say,
"Jackson, this camping is..."

02:31.420 --> 02:33.120
Is not hell.

02:33.120 --> 02:34.290
[ Chuckles ]

02:34.290 --> 02:37.830
I'll take that.

02:37.830 --> 02:39.250
Ow. Ow. Ow.

02:39.250 --> 02:40.380
What is it?
Mnh.

02:40.380 --> 02:41.420
What is that,
root or rock?

02:41.420 --> 02:42.540
Uh, unclear.

02:42.540 --> 02:44.920
Yeah, right.
I can fix that.

02:44.920 --> 02:46.040
♪♪

02:46.040 --> 02:47.540
Can I have
some more juice?

02:47.540 --> 02:49.080
Sure.

02:49.080 --> 02:50.540
[ Cellphone beeps ]
Ugh.

02:50.540 --> 02:52.750
Schmitt.
You have her? She's landed?

02:52.750 --> 02:54.290
Okay, okay, okay.

02:54.290 --> 02:56.420
Look, just call me the second
you get in the car, please?

02:56.420 --> 02:57.620
And -- And be careful.

02:57.620 --> 03:00.460
Don't -- Don't break her
and don't spill her.

03:00.460 --> 03:01.830
"Don't spill her"?

03:01.830 --> 03:03.710
Yeah. I found
a blood donor for Gus.

03:03.710 --> 03:04.880
She's the only match
in the world.

03:04.880 --> 03:06.290
She just came in
from London,

03:06.290 --> 03:07.750
so we got to move,
Zola.

03:07.750 --> 03:10.540
Uh, yeah. Let's, uh,
eat up and get out.

03:10.540 --> 03:12.670
How much longer is Mommy staying
with Aunt Jo?

03:12.670 --> 03:15.330
Till Mommy helps Aunt Jo
feel better.

03:15.330 --> 03:17.460
What's wrong
with Aunt Jo?

03:17.460 --> 03:19.750
Okay, Zola.
Let's move.

03:19.750 --> 03:21.620
Go have a shower.
I got 'em.

03:23.460 --> 03:25.920
Alex, if anyone can help,
it's Meredith.

03:25.920 --> 03:27.460
Go.

03:27.460 --> 03:29.960
[ Birds chirping ]

03:31.330 --> 03:33.500
[ Sirens wailing in distance ]

03:33.500 --> 03:36.000
Woman on PA:
Dr. Macriola to Pediatrics.

03:36.000 --> 03:38.250
Dr. Macriola to Pediatrics.

03:38.250 --> 03:39.330
[ Toy squeaks ]

03:39.330 --> 03:40.750
Hm? Ah.

03:40.750 --> 03:41.790
[ Giggles ]
[ Laughs ]

03:41.790 --> 03:43.210
Buenos días, Gabby.

03:43.210 --> 03:44.920
Buenos días.

03:44.920 --> 03:47.250
Hey.
I thought we were friends.

03:47.250 --> 03:49.170
Hey. Hey. Huh? Okay.

03:49.170 --> 03:51.290
Oh, it's a war now, huh?
Okay.

03:51.290 --> 03:53.500
Woman on PA:
Dr. Boyle to Cardiology.

03:53.500 --> 03:56.460
Dr. Boyle to Cardiology.

03:56.460 --> 03:58.460
Hey, if I'd have known
you were coming in,

03:58.460 --> 03:59.920
I'd have waited
to give you a ride.

03:59.920 --> 04:02.500
I didn't know
I was coming.

04:02.500 --> 04:04.170
Is everything okay?

04:04.170 --> 04:06.330
[ Sighs ]
Foundation business.

04:06.330 --> 04:07.420
Dr. Bailey.

04:07.420 --> 04:08.460
[ Door creaks ]

04:08.460 --> 04:09.540
Good morning,
Dr. Webber.

04:09.540 --> 04:11.500
Well,
the jury's out on that.

04:11.500 --> 04:13.210
What's going on
in there?

04:13.210 --> 04:14.670
[ Leo babbles ]

04:14.670 --> 04:17.040
Nothing good.

04:18.790 --> 04:20.250
Picked a crib?

04:20.250 --> 04:21.500
No,
but I'm picturing one,

04:21.500 --> 04:22.790
and it won't go with
[laughs] that.
W-- W--

04:22.790 --> 04:25.790
Well, I just -- I want her --
her nursery to be perfect.

04:25.790 --> 04:28.420
And perfection is the absence
of all material objects?

04:28.420 --> 04:31.420
What?
No, I'll know it
when I see it.

04:31.420 --> 04:33.210
And you're sure
no one saw you?

04:33.210 --> 04:34.830
No one saw me
because no one was home.

04:34.830 --> 04:36.170
I could have
walked around naked.

04:37.420 --> 04:38.830
I didn't.

04:38.830 --> 04:41.420
Kari Donnelly, injected with
stem cells 13 days ago

04:41.420 --> 04:44.290
in hopes of restoring
upper-body mobility.

04:44.290 --> 04:46.670
She's been on vanc and Zosyn
for the last week

04:46.670 --> 04:48.420
for persistent
pneumonia.

04:48.420 --> 04:51.170
Teddy:
We performed a bronchoscopy to
clear her lungs and her airways,

04:51.170 --> 04:52.670
but I'd also
like to do a CT

04:52.670 --> 04:53.920
and just check to see
what's going on.

04:53.920 --> 04:55.830
She can't even cough.

04:55.830 --> 04:57.120
I can't believe this.

04:57.120 --> 04:59.330
How are we doing today,
Kari?

04:59.330 --> 05:01.670
Any pain or tingling
in your arms, fingers?

05:01.670 --> 05:03.290
Still nothing.

05:03.290 --> 05:04.380
You said
we'd know in two weeks.

05:04.380 --> 05:05.830
I-I-Is it the pneumonia?

05:05.830 --> 05:06.790
Is that why the stem cells
aren't working?

05:06.790 --> 05:08.170
There's still time.

05:08.170 --> 05:10.420
Toby is
such a pessimist.

05:10.420 --> 05:12.540
I blame their father.
He's a real jerk.

05:12.540 --> 05:14.540
Hopefully, you'll be able to
flip him off soon.

05:14.540 --> 05:17.080
[ Chuckles ]

05:17.080 --> 05:18.120
[ Telephone rings in distance ]

05:18.120 --> 05:19.250
[ Monitor beeping ]

05:19.250 --> 05:20.540
Is the blood donor here?

05:20.540 --> 05:22.960
Well, she flew in from London.
Her plane has landed.

05:22.960 --> 05:24.580
Oh, thank God.

05:24.580 --> 05:26.500
We had a terrible night.
Gus can't sleep.

05:26.500 --> 05:27.750
He won't build his LEGOs.

05:27.750 --> 05:29.210
I should get an update any --
[ Cellphone vibrates, rings ]

05:29.210 --> 05:31.000
Oh, hang on.

05:31.000 --> 05:33.420
Here it is.
Go, Schmitt.

05:33.420 --> 05:35.960
Schmitt: We are almost
on the ground.

05:35.960 --> 05:36.960
Wait.
You said they'd landed.

05:36.960 --> 05:38.420
Sorry, I meant --
I meant she.

05:38.420 --> 05:39.960
She is almost
on the ground.

05:39.960 --> 05:41.580
Oh.
She's just really scared.

05:41.580 --> 05:43.210
[ Breathing heavily ]

05:43.210 --> 05:44.880
Good, good, Frances.
Four more steps.

05:44.880 --> 05:46.790
Her agoraphobia is way worse
than we thought.

05:46.790 --> 05:49.000
I mean, s-s-she seems like
she's afraid of the air.

05:49.000 --> 05:50.960
Oh, dear, dear, dear.

05:50.960 --> 05:52.290
I can't do this.

05:52.290 --> 05:53.830
Yes, you can.
I've got you, Frances.

05:53.830 --> 05:55.460
Okay, hold on.
Hold on.

05:55.460 --> 05:57.170
Mm, yes!

05:57.170 --> 05:58.460
See?
You're perfectly all right.

05:58.460 --> 05:59.880
We're good.
Eagle has landed.

05:59.880 --> 06:01.000
[ Chuckles ]

06:01.000 --> 06:02.460
Sir, wait right there.

06:02.460 --> 06:04.330
Uh, wait, wait.
Dr. Safavi.

06:04.330 --> 06:05.540
Something's happening.

06:05.540 --> 06:06.960
What do you mean?

06:06.960 --> 06:08.210
Uh, is --
is there a problem?

06:08.210 --> 06:10.380
It appears there's a question
about my visa.

06:10.380 --> 06:11.710
Come with us, please.

06:11.710 --> 06:14.000
Oh, I -- But he --
No, I'm so-- I'm sorry.

06:14.000 --> 06:15.290
You can't --
He's --

06:15.290 --> 06:17.380
It will be all right, Frances!
Keep breathing!

06:17.380 --> 06:18.880
Uh, customs is taking
her therapist.

06:18.880 --> 06:20.080
Alex: Wait, Schmitt,
listen to me.

06:20.080 --> 06:21.540
You need to get Frances
here now.

06:21.540 --> 06:24.500
♪♪

06:24.500 --> 06:26.580
Ms. Pinfield,
this is no cause for alarm.

06:26.580 --> 06:28.830
Why don't we just go --
I should like to go home now.

06:28.830 --> 06:30.500
I have to go home.
Wait.

06:30.500 --> 06:31.500
W-W-Wait. Uh...

06:31.500 --> 06:32.790
Schmitt.

06:32.790 --> 06:34.120
Oh, she's back on the plane!
I got to go!

06:34.120 --> 06:35.620
Schmitt?!

06:35.620 --> 06:39.750
♪♪

06:41.380 --> 06:43.290
What is it?
What's wrong?

06:43.290 --> 06:44.670
The donor's still
on the plane.

06:44.670 --> 06:46.250
She's really scared.

06:46.250 --> 06:49.330
There's some kind of mix-up
with her therapist and customs.

06:49.330 --> 06:50.620
But we'll figure it out.

06:50.620 --> 06:51.830
We're -- We're just
gonna have to

06:51.830 --> 06:53.040
wait a little bit longer,
okay?

06:53.040 --> 06:55.420
That's all anyone's been
saying to us for weeks...

06:55.420 --> 06:57.960
is to wait,
and wait some more.

06:57.960 --> 07:00.710
And wait and wait
and wait!

07:00.710 --> 07:03.330
[ Voice breaking ]
Look at my son!

07:03.330 --> 07:05.540
He's getting sicker
and sicker

07:05.540 --> 07:07.790
while we just sit here
doing what we're told.

07:07.790 --> 07:10.830
He's dying!

07:10.830 --> 07:13.500
And she won't
get off the plane?!

07:13.500 --> 07:15.080
[ Gasps ]
Whoa.

07:15.080 --> 07:16.670
I'm sorry.
I'm sorry.

07:16.670 --> 07:18.670
It's okay.

07:18.670 --> 07:20.000
I kinda want
to smash one, too.

07:20.000 --> 07:22.290
[ Crying ]
I've got it, baby.

07:22.290 --> 07:23.710
[ Yells ]

07:23.710 --> 07:25.170
[ Groans ]
Whoa.

07:25.170 --> 07:26.790
-[ Groans ]
-Oh, babe.

07:26.790 --> 07:27.790
[ Breathing heavily ]

07:27.790 --> 07:28.790
Are you okay?

07:28.790 --> 07:30.670
Ye-- No!

07:30.670 --> 07:32.750
[ Grunts ]

07:32.750 --> 07:33.750
I don't think so.

07:33.750 --> 07:34.790
Okay. Stay still.

07:34.790 --> 07:35.790
[ Groans ]

07:49.670 --> 07:51.000
What happened?!
He took a nasty fall,

07:51.000 --> 07:52.000
landed extremely hard
on his --

07:52.000 --> 07:53.540
It was my ass!

07:53.540 --> 07:55.620
Can you even break your ass?
Does that happen?

07:55.620 --> 07:56.920
Sadly, yes.

07:56.920 --> 07:57.710
Is this
the broken coccyx?

07:57.710 --> 07:59.040
I paged Link.

07:59.040 --> 08:00.420
You paged ortho.

08:00.420 --> 08:02.710
Forget about me.
Just get that donor for my son.

08:02.710 --> 08:03.880
Please.

08:03.880 --> 08:05.080
What donor?
What happened?

08:05.080 --> 08:06.880
The golden donor landed,
but she's agoraphobic,

08:06.880 --> 08:08.710
and Schmitt can't get her
off the plane.

08:08.710 --> 08:11.080
I'd go,
but I need eyes on Gus.

08:11.080 --> 08:12.540
Listen, I'll go.
I'll give her a sedative.

08:12.540 --> 08:13.670
I'll bring
a blood donor kit.
All right.

08:13.670 --> 08:15.750
I'll get your blood, Karev.
Drive fast!

08:16.830 --> 08:20.040
♪ Wake me up
before you go-go ♪
[ Sighs ]

08:20.040 --> 08:22.710
♪ I'm not planning
on going solo ♪

08:22.710 --> 08:25.250
Frances,
I am begging you.

08:25.250 --> 08:28.290
Literally,
I am begging you.

08:28.290 --> 08:30.420
I'm sorry.
The singing helps.

08:30.420 --> 08:32.669
Dr. Safavi says
it helps my mind to focus.

08:32.669 --> 08:34.460
I'm not talking about
the singing.

08:34.460 --> 08:36.210
A kid is dying.

08:36.210 --> 08:38.880
♪ I don't want to miss you
when you hit that high ♪
[ Groans ]

08:38.880 --> 08:41.500
Nico's covering
my service.

08:41.500 --> 08:44.500
I'll keep Toby company
while Kari's in CT.

08:44.500 --> 08:46.120
The waiting's
killing them.

08:46.120 --> 08:48.290
I-I think I might be wrong
about Malibu Barbie.

08:48.290 --> 08:50.500
He really might be, uh,
marriage material.

08:50.500 --> 08:51.830
What?

08:51.830 --> 08:54.170
I thought giving each other
unwanted romantic advice

08:54.170 --> 08:56.040
was our thing?
It's not.

08:56.960 --> 08:58.710
What is happening?

08:58.710 --> 09:00.500
No clue.

09:00.500 --> 09:02.670
But they've been in there
coming up on an hour.

09:02.670 --> 09:04.710
Hm. I once saw Catherine fire
a whole cardio department

09:04.710 --> 09:05.790
in five minutes.

09:05.790 --> 09:07.830
It's major.

09:07.830 --> 09:10.710
Could be a new scandal
with the Foundation.

09:10.710 --> 09:12.960
Or maybe she's selling
the hospital.

09:12.960 --> 09:14.670
Don't you think
you'd know

09:14.670 --> 09:16.420
if your wife was
selling the hospital?

09:19.670 --> 09:22.170
Yeah. Forget I asked.

09:22.170 --> 09:29.250
♪♪

09:29.250 --> 09:31.330
[ Chuckles ]

09:31.330 --> 09:33.710
You know...

09:33.710 --> 09:35.460
Hm?

09:35.460 --> 09:37.790
I was thinking,

09:37.790 --> 09:40.040
we could...

09:40.040 --> 09:43.080
go hiking
up to the waterfalls.

09:43.080 --> 09:46.380
Or you could go hiking,

09:46.380 --> 09:48.500
and I could stay here
and read.

09:48.500 --> 09:50.920
Yeah, but...

09:50.920 --> 09:53.540
there's this spot
I want to show you

09:53.540 --> 09:56.830
I found
last time I was here.

09:56.830 --> 09:59.670
Okay. Let's do it.

09:59.670 --> 10:00.710
Really?

10:00.710 --> 10:03.540
Yeah. Really.

10:03.540 --> 10:06.580
Hey, look,
if I'm going camping...

10:06.580 --> 10:08.120
I am going camping.

10:10.880 --> 10:12.210
We're wasting time.

10:12.210 --> 10:13.460
I already know
he broke his coccyx.

10:13.460 --> 10:15.120
He's got
a textbook presentation.

10:15.120 --> 10:16.920
"Textbook"
implies certainty,

10:16.920 --> 10:18.580
which I prefer to
get from the scans.

10:18.580 --> 10:20.710
[ Sighs ]
Did you page me?

10:20.710 --> 10:22.540
Oh, yeah. Are you available
to take this one?

10:22.540 --> 10:24.500
I need to be on call
for Karev's thymoma kid

10:24.500 --> 10:25.580
when the blood arrives.

10:25.580 --> 10:26.670
All right.
What do we have?

10:26.670 --> 10:27.960
The dude fell.

10:27.960 --> 10:29.540
[ Beeping ]
Oh, scans came in.

10:29.540 --> 10:30.830
Wow, wow.

10:30.830 --> 10:32.420
Would you look at that?

10:32.420 --> 10:34.080
He broke his coccyx.

10:34.080 --> 10:36.750
And he punctured
his rectum.

10:36.750 --> 10:39.330
That's a nasty business.

10:39.330 --> 10:40.670
Thanks, Altman.
I needed this.

10:40.670 --> 10:42.620
You needed
a punctured rectum?

10:42.620 --> 10:44.620
[ Chuckling ]
I needed a distraction

10:44.620 --> 10:47.290
from whatever's going on
in the conference room.

10:47.290 --> 10:48.250
Teddy: Thank you
for taking this one.

10:58.330 --> 10:59.960
[ Breathes deeply ]

10:59.960 --> 11:01.670
Why don't you
go take a shower?

11:01.670 --> 11:03.040
You don't
have to go anywhere.
[ Sighs ]

11:03.040 --> 11:05.080
I told you,
I don't need you to fix me.

11:05.080 --> 11:07.080
I'm not trying
to fix you.

11:07.080 --> 11:08.120
Right.

11:08.120 --> 11:10.290
You're here because

11:10.290 --> 11:12.620
you're too scared to
deal with your own crap,

11:12.620 --> 11:14.120
so you bury your head
in medicine

11:14.120 --> 11:16.540
or everyone else's lives.

11:16.540 --> 11:19.000
Maybe the tiniest part of me
is hiding out here

11:19.000 --> 11:20.880
'cause it's easier
than facing Andrew.

11:20.880 --> 11:22.040
Because he loves you?

11:22.040 --> 11:23.790
Because he said
he loved me.

11:23.790 --> 11:26.120
To my face.

11:26.120 --> 11:27.750
Out loud.

11:27.750 --> 11:31.500
And all that love staring me
in the face is terrifying.

11:31.500 --> 11:34.080
That doesn't mean that
I'm not mostly here for you.

11:36.210 --> 11:38.750
Go home, Meredith.
I'm not asking.

11:38.750 --> 11:42.380
But I promised Alex that I would
stay here until you talk to me.

11:42.380 --> 11:44.880
You come here,
you sleep in my bed,

11:44.880 --> 11:46.620
and complain about
all this love,

11:46.620 --> 11:48.620
and you think that somehow
that's gonna help me?

11:48.620 --> 11:51.620
My husband died.
Let's be clear.

11:51.620 --> 11:53.330
♪♪

11:53.330 --> 11:55.170
The "I love you" scares me

11:55.170 --> 11:57.580
because the last person
I said it to was Derek.

11:57.580 --> 11:59.710
I'm not a delicate flower.

11:59.710 --> 12:02.790
I'm not a person who doesn't
understand pain.

12:02.790 --> 12:06.080
I get it
from deep experience.

12:06.080 --> 12:10.080
Plus my parents --
they screwed with my head

12:10.080 --> 12:11.460
in more ways
than I can count.

12:11.460 --> 12:14.080
His parents, too,
so there isn't anything

12:14.080 --> 12:16.580
that we can't handle
or that we wouldn't understand.

12:19.380 --> 12:21.330
Was your mother raped?

12:21.330 --> 12:23.170
♪♪

12:23.170 --> 12:25.670
Was your mother raped
by your father?

12:25.670 --> 12:28.380
Is that why you exist?

12:28.380 --> 12:31.580
Do you look
like a rapist?

12:31.580 --> 12:33.710
Do you wear his face?

12:35.750 --> 12:37.830
Okay, then.

12:37.830 --> 12:39.880
I don't think
you do get this,

12:39.880 --> 12:42.670
so please go home.

12:42.670 --> 12:48.710
♪♪

12:54.330 --> 12:56.960
Oh, aren't you
so glad you came?

12:56.960 --> 12:59.830
Yeah.
Yeah, I feel refreshed.

12:59.830 --> 13:02.000
[ Chuckles ]

13:02.000 --> 13:03.880
I'm trying.

13:03.880 --> 13:06.960
Ah.
I know, babe.

13:06.960 --> 13:08.710
I appreciate it.
Ah.

13:08.710 --> 13:11.120
[ Birds chirping ]

13:16.620 --> 13:18.710
It's kind of nice
seeing you in your element.

13:18.710 --> 13:19.750
[ Insect buzzes ]

13:19.750 --> 13:21.460
Ow. Ow.
What? What? What?

13:21.460 --> 13:22.710
Ow. Ow. Ow! Ow!

13:22.710 --> 13:24.540
What?
Ow! I-I don't know.

13:24.540 --> 13:26.080
Um, a bee sting?
Bite?

13:26.080 --> 13:27.420
A spider bite?
I-I don't know.

13:27.420 --> 13:29.250
Okay. All right. Oh, God.
That's swelling up fast.

13:29.250 --> 13:31.120
What are you allergic to?
I don't know.

13:31.120 --> 13:32.330
What do you mean
you don't know?

13:32.330 --> 13:34.250
I --
I don't go camping!

13:34.250 --> 13:36.290
Maggie, all right.
Okay.

13:36.290 --> 13:38.000
Let's get -- We'll get some ice
on it back at the tent, okay?

13:38.000 --> 13:39.920
-[ Whimpering ]
-Okay, settle down.

13:39.920 --> 13:42.250
[ Buzzing continues ]
Just stay in one place --
Just stay in one place!

13:42.250 --> 13:43.460
Maggie, hold on!
Oh!

13:43.460 --> 13:45.040
Aah!
God.

13:45.040 --> 13:46.120
All right. Okay.

13:46.120 --> 13:48.170
[ Groans ]

13:48.170 --> 13:50.960
See, and then the picture comes
up right here when it's ready.

13:50.960 --> 13:52.750
Woman on PA: Dr. Downs
to the Step-down Unit.

13:52.750 --> 13:54.380
Dr. Downs
to the Step-down Unit.

13:54.380 --> 13:56.170
Hey, Gabby.
What's going on?

13:56.170 --> 13:59.000
Hey. Just showing Gabby
how the MRI works.

13:59.000 --> 14:00.210
[ Quietly ] How's Jo?

14:00.210 --> 14:02.670
No idea.
Mer's still over there.

14:02.670 --> 14:04.250
You've probably heard
more than me.

14:04.250 --> 14:05.710
No, I actually haven't
heard from her in a while.

14:05.710 --> 14:07.170
Well, that's why.

14:07.170 --> 14:08.250
Ah. Maybe.

14:08.250 --> 14:09.790
[ Computer beeps ]

14:09.790 --> 14:13.040
There she is!
[ Chuckles ]

14:13.040 --> 14:14.920
She's a little scared
about the MRI,

14:14.920 --> 14:17.250
so I said we'd test it on
her little kitty, Perla, first.

14:17.250 --> 14:18.750
Right? Mm-hmm.

14:18.750 --> 14:19.710
You should be in peds.

14:19.710 --> 14:21.330
[ Laughs ]

14:21.330 --> 14:24.420
See?
She's okay, right?

14:24.420 --> 14:26.540
[ Train horn blares ]

14:26.540 --> 14:31.670
I remember playing
in this crappy playground

14:31.670 --> 14:33.710
when I was 7.

14:33.710 --> 14:36.750
My foster brothers wanted
nothing to do with me,

14:36.750 --> 14:40.580
and my foster dad -- he was just
screaming by the swings

14:40.580 --> 14:43.170
about I don't know what.

14:43.170 --> 14:45.790
[ Exhaling deeply ]
And there was this girl

14:45.790 --> 14:49.170
with these freckles
and bright red pigtails --

14:49.170 --> 14:52.920
and she went sliding down
this yellow slide,

14:52.920 --> 14:56.670
and she just crashed
right into the concrete.

14:56.670 --> 15:00.080
And I remember her mom
just ran over

15:00.080 --> 15:03.330
and scooped her up
and held her,

15:03.330 --> 15:07.420
and, you know, she didn't care
about the blood on her shirt

15:07.420 --> 15:09.330
or the snot running down
her shoulders.

15:09.330 --> 15:12.290
She just --
She just whispered,

15:12.290 --> 15:14.420
"I'm sorry,"
in her daughter's ear,

15:14.420 --> 15:17.540
and she just kept holding her
and holding her

15:17.540 --> 15:20.790
until she felt like
it was safe to let go.

15:20.790 --> 15:23.580
My whole life,
I was convinced that,

15:23.580 --> 15:28.250
if I ever met my mom,
she would do the same,

15:28.250 --> 15:31.830
that she would say
she was sorry,

15:31.830 --> 15:35.540
and she would hold me
until I felt safe.

15:35.540 --> 15:39.420
♪♪

15:39.420 --> 15:41.710
But that's not ever
gonna happen...

15:41.710 --> 15:43.830
♪♪

15:43.830 --> 15:47.120
...because I never should have
existed in the first place.

15:47.120 --> 15:50.120
Paul?
Everything he did to me?

15:50.120 --> 15:53.460
Everything I escaped?

15:53.460 --> 15:56.290
That was my birthright,
Meredith.

16:00.080 --> 16:01.920
That was my inheritance.

16:01.920 --> 16:05.380
♪♪

16:09.460 --> 16:12.080
Dr. Hunt?
Oh, Dr. Hunt is here. Thank God.

16:12.080 --> 16:15.540
Frances, this is
the very terrific Dr. Hunt.

16:15.540 --> 16:17.380
Hello, Frances --
Did you happen to see
Dr. Safavi?

16:17.380 --> 16:18.460
He's my therapist.

16:18.460 --> 16:20.000
Uh, I think --
I think that's --

16:20.000 --> 16:21.500
I think he's --
it's gonna take a while.
He's lovely.

16:21.500 --> 16:23.710
Been working with me
for about two years now.

16:23.710 --> 16:25.620
"Exposure therapy,"
he calls it.

16:25.620 --> 16:28.290
We go outside,
little bits by bits,

16:28.290 --> 16:31.540
to the garden, to the curb,
then we did a cornershop.

16:31.540 --> 16:33.170
Oh, so you went shopping,
Frances?

16:33.170 --> 16:34.880
No.
Just stood there.

16:34.880 --> 16:36.420
Had a bit of a panic.

16:36.420 --> 16:38.710
Had a little fall down once,
but I got to the point

16:38.710 --> 16:40.750
where I could do 10 minutes
and then go home.

16:40.750 --> 16:42.960
And then --
then I got a phone call,

16:42.960 --> 16:46.380
and they said, "You could help
someone with your blood,

16:46.380 --> 16:48.330
but you have to travel
on two planes

16:48.330 --> 16:51.500
across the sea
to another country."

16:51.500 --> 16:53.620
And I went to Dr. Safavi,
and I said,

16:53.620 --> 16:55.500
"Do you think
I'm ready for that?"

16:55.500 --> 16:56.710
And do you know
what he said?

16:56.710 --> 16:58.250
No.
Nothing.

16:58.250 --> 16:59.710
Oh?
Not a sound.

16:59.710 --> 17:02.250
He just gaped at me
with his mouth open,

17:02.250 --> 17:04.040
as if he'd forgotten
all the words for "No,"

17:04.040 --> 17:06.170
but I said, "I want to help,
if I can."

17:06.170 --> 17:08.079
And I truly did,

17:08.079 --> 17:11.670
[Voice breaking]
but it appears -- I'm so sorry.

17:11.670 --> 17:13.579
It appears
that he was right.

17:13.579 --> 17:15.750
It appears I can't.
I'm so sorry.

17:15.750 --> 17:17.210
Ma'am, it is okay.

17:17.210 --> 17:19.540
We have this all figured out,
and I --

17:19.540 --> 17:22.040
I'm just gonna
take your blood right here,

17:22.040 --> 17:23.210
and then you can
just stay here --

17:23.210 --> 17:25.210
You are not sticking me
with that.

17:25.210 --> 17:27.250
You flew all this way
to donate your blood.

17:27.250 --> 17:28.790
What did you think
was gonna --
In hospital.

17:28.790 --> 17:31.120
Not on a tiny,
little aeroplane.

17:31.120 --> 17:32.620
[ Breathes sharply ]

17:32.620 --> 17:35.000
You could stab me wrong.
I could bleed to death.

17:35.000 --> 17:36.290
Ma'am --
There's no one
to give me any blood.

17:36.290 --> 17:37.750
I could catch
a hideous infection.

17:37.750 --> 17:39.000
Frances --

17:39.000 --> 17:41.500
You could send an air bubble
into my brain

17:41.500 --> 17:43.960
that pops
and makes my eyes go wonky.

17:43.960 --> 17:45.250
I read about that.
Ma'am, ma'am, please --

17:45.250 --> 17:47.540
No, no, no, no, no.
Ma'am, please --

17:47.540 --> 17:49.830
I never should have come.
Please don't kill me.

17:49.830 --> 17:52.210
[ Breathing heavily ]

17:52.210 --> 17:55.290
♪ Wake me up
before you go-go ♪

17:55.290 --> 17:57.170
Scott's on his way
up to the O.R. now.

17:57.170 --> 17:58.380
[ Crying ]

17:58.380 --> 18:00.120
As bad as it sounds,
it's a straightforward repair.

18:00.120 --> 18:03.170
As long as he takes it easy and
heals properly, he'll be okay.

18:03.170 --> 18:04.710
I promise.

18:04.710 --> 18:07.380
[ Laughing ]

18:07.380 --> 18:09.380
I'm sorry.

18:09.380 --> 18:12.790
I'm so sorry. I just --
Oh, I can't stop laughing.

18:12.790 --> 18:14.880
[ Laughs ]

18:14.880 --> 18:16.790
I called my mom
to tell her what happened,

18:16.790 --> 18:18.500
but -- but I had to
hang up the phone

18:18.500 --> 18:21.380
because I was [Laughing]
laughing too hard.

18:21.380 --> 18:23.920
And -- And I know
that Scott is upset

18:23.920 --> 18:26.290
and -- and --
and in pain,

18:26.290 --> 18:29.750
and -- and it's awful.

18:29.750 --> 18:33.460
But, for weeks,

18:33.460 --> 18:37.460
I've just been sick
about this,

18:37.460 --> 18:40.830
and for the first time,
I've had 10 minutes where

18:40.830 --> 18:43.830
[Voice breaking] I didn't
have to worry about my son.

18:43.830 --> 18:45.210
[ Sighs, sniffles ]

18:45.210 --> 18:47.170
Because my husband
broke his butt.

18:47.170 --> 18:48.460
[ Laughs ]

18:48.460 --> 18:51.120
Oh, God.

18:51.120 --> 18:52.790
Oh, God,
and his rectum.
[ Chuckles ]

18:52.790 --> 18:55.880
Ah, that's got to
hurt like hell.

18:55.880 --> 18:58.040
Is he gonna have to sit on
one of those doughnut thingies?

18:58.040 --> 18:59.540
[ Laughs ]

18:59.540 --> 19:01.460
[ Chuckles ]

19:01.460 --> 19:02.670
[ Gasps ]
[ Monitor beeping rapidly ]

19:02.670 --> 19:03.710
Oh, no!

19:03.710 --> 19:04.710
Gus? Gus?

19:04.710 --> 19:05.710
Oh, God. Baby?

19:05.710 --> 19:06.710
Oh, no.

19:06.710 --> 19:08.000
What's happening?

19:08.000 --> 19:09.170
Gus?
What's happening to him?

19:09.170 --> 19:10.250
Gus?
What's happening?!

19:10.250 --> 19:11.540
I need a crash cart
in here!

19:11.540 --> 19:12.880
Gus?! Baby, are you okay?!
What's happening?!

19:12.880 --> 19:15.080
What's happening?!

19:20.750 --> 19:24.080
Woman on PA:
Dr. Baxter to Radiology.
Dr. Baxter to Radiology.

19:24.080 --> 19:25.960
[ Indistinct conversations ]

19:25.960 --> 19:27.960
Please tell me
Kari's improving.

19:27.960 --> 19:29.710
Still nothing.

19:29.710 --> 19:31.170
It should be working,
right?

19:31.170 --> 19:32.250
I mean, if she's not
moving by now --

19:32.250 --> 19:34.580
Well,
it still might work.

19:34.580 --> 19:37.040
Is this the, uh, secret meeting
everyone's talking about?

19:37.040 --> 19:38.920
Yeah.
People are taking bets on

19:38.920 --> 19:41.620
what Bailey and Catherine are
deciding about our future.

19:41.620 --> 19:44.210
My money's on
a mountain of new funding.

19:44.210 --> 19:46.670
How do you do that?

19:46.670 --> 19:48.460
Just assume the best?

19:48.460 --> 19:51.500
I mean, at a y-young
and formative age,

19:51.500 --> 19:53.830
you said,
"Ouch, my leg hurts,"

19:53.830 --> 19:55.880
and the doctor all but
gave you a death sentence.

19:55.880 --> 20:00.040
So how do you not
always assume the worst?

20:00.040 --> 20:01.710
Because the worst
already happened.

20:01.710 --> 20:03.830
I guess I think life's got to
give you some good apples

20:03.830 --> 20:06.460
along with the rotten ones,
right, for balance?

20:06.460 --> 20:09.580
I'm not sure
that's how life works.

20:09.580 --> 20:13.540
No one's sure how life works,
but I like my theory.

20:13.540 --> 20:15.210
Works for me.

20:18.960 --> 20:20.540
Nico:
Removing coccygeal fragments.

20:20.540 --> 20:21.880
Okay, easy.

20:21.880 --> 20:23.460
[ Monitor beeping ]

20:23.460 --> 20:25.960
Good.

20:25.960 --> 20:28.790
Dr. Kim, I finished reviewing
your pre-op films,

20:28.790 --> 20:30.580
removed Mr. Peña's drain,

20:30.580 --> 20:32.790
and checked on your clinic
schedule for tomorrow.

20:32.790 --> 20:34.290
Can I scrub in
on the broken butt?

20:34.290 --> 20:36.330
It's a fractured coccyx
and a rectal tear.

20:36.330 --> 20:37.170
The whole floor
was talking about

20:37.170 --> 20:38.210
how his wife
threw a tantrum

20:38.210 --> 20:39.540
and started chucking
his toys everywhere --

20:39.540 --> 20:41.880
Because they're scared their son
is gonna die, Helm!

20:41.880 --> 20:44.830
Uh, I'm -- I'm sorry.

20:44.830 --> 20:46.380
I-I didn't mean to --

20:46.380 --> 20:48.040
Look, Helm.
We got it covered here,

20:48.040 --> 20:49.620
so just head back out
to the floor

20:49.620 --> 20:51.750
and do afternoon rounds
on all my post-ops, all right?

20:51.750 --> 20:53.960
[ Beeping continues ]

20:53.960 --> 20:55.420
[ Liquid suctioning ]
[ Sighs ]

20:57.670 --> 21:01.540
Dr. Kim,
the man broke his butt.

21:01.540 --> 21:03.330
And?

21:03.330 --> 21:05.380
I'm saying it's funny.

21:05.380 --> 21:06.790
And I'm saying
Helm did nothing wrong.

21:06.790 --> 21:08.120
I disagree.

21:08.120 --> 21:10.380
Look, we have to
allow ourselves to laugh

21:10.380 --> 21:12.790
at the soda bottles
we pull out of rectums

21:12.790 --> 21:15.920
or -- or the Judy doll heads
that we pull out of stomachs.

21:15.920 --> 21:18.580
If we don't find
some lightness and humor

21:18.580 --> 21:20.120
in this darkness
we face every day,

21:20.120 --> 21:21.830
no one would stay
in this job.

21:21.830 --> 21:23.500
[ Liquid suctioning ]

21:23.500 --> 21:24.880
[ Beeping continues ]

21:24.880 --> 21:26.920
Thank you, sir.

21:26.920 --> 21:28.580
3-0 vicryl.

21:28.580 --> 21:30.460
[ Beeping continues ]

21:34.290 --> 21:37.210
We have pills. We have shots.
Simple sedatives.

21:37.210 --> 21:39.460
But I've never
taken them.

21:39.460 --> 21:41.750
What if I have
an allergic reaction?

21:41.750 --> 21:43.830
And we're not in a hospital
where you can treat it.

21:43.830 --> 21:45.210
Listen, the chances of that
are very --

21:45.210 --> 21:46.460
Are they none at all?

21:46.460 --> 21:48.080
[ Sighs ]

21:48.080 --> 21:51.710
Frances, I hate to
suggest this, but...

21:51.710 --> 21:53.120
maybe if you put the blanket
over your head

21:53.120 --> 21:54.500
between here and the car,
then we can just --

21:54.500 --> 21:55.710
I can't leave here.
I can't.

21:55.710 --> 21:57.790
You can, though.
I can't. I can't.

21:57.790 --> 21:59.790
You can
because you promised.

21:59.790 --> 22:01.420
Owen: Schmitt.

22:01.420 --> 22:04.120
There is no other
golden blood donor.

22:04.120 --> 22:06.750
You are a unicorn,
you are Bigfoot,

22:06.750 --> 22:08.330
and you said yes.

22:08.330 --> 22:10.210
And now you can't just decide
you don't want to.

22:10.210 --> 22:11.420
Schmitt, Schmitt, come here.
Come here.

22:11.420 --> 22:12.880
Someone's
going to die here.

22:12.880 --> 22:14.210
Schmitt!

22:14.210 --> 22:17.330
I could die!

22:17.330 --> 22:19.620
I was taught,
from a little girl,

22:19.620 --> 22:22.380
that my body is like
a china cup,

22:22.380 --> 22:24.670
and I mustn't ever,
ever break it.

22:24.670 --> 22:27.380
And I know --
well, part of me knows --

22:27.380 --> 22:29.210
that I'm not gonna
break into pieces

22:29.210 --> 22:30.580
if I walk down
to the cornershop

22:30.580 --> 22:32.380
or if I go to
the cinema.

22:32.380 --> 22:35.500
But there's another part
that knows that, if I do,

22:35.500 --> 22:39.000
if I hurt myself, if I bleed,
I will die,

22:39.000 --> 22:41.420
and no one can help me.

22:41.420 --> 22:44.080
That part won't allow it.

22:44.080 --> 22:47.250
And that part
always wins.

22:47.250 --> 22:49.750
I'm sorry.

22:49.750 --> 22:51.750
I want to help,
but I can't.

22:51.750 --> 22:53.420
But you want to.

22:53.420 --> 22:54.710
I came all this way.

22:54.710 --> 22:57.750
I have an idea,
something that might help.

22:59.540 --> 23:02.290
Lori, we were hoping to operate
after the transfusion,

23:02.290 --> 23:04.120
but now we'd like
to wait a few days

23:04.120 --> 23:05.790
and give Gus's heart
time to heal.

23:05.790 --> 23:07.210
How will it heal?

23:07.210 --> 23:08.330
From the blood.

23:08.330 --> 23:10.960
Okay.

23:10.960 --> 23:12.250
[ Cellphone beeping ]

23:12.250 --> 23:13.540
Altman, wait.

23:13.540 --> 23:15.080
It's Hunt.

23:15.080 --> 23:17.170
Owen: Hey, Dr. Karev.
This is Frances.

23:17.170 --> 23:18.460
Frances:
[ Weakly ] Hello.

23:18.460 --> 23:20.790
Can, uh -- Frances
would like to meet Gus.

23:20.790 --> 23:22.960
Yeah, right here.

23:22.960 --> 23:25.080
Frances is frightened,

23:25.080 --> 23:26.620
deeply frightened
to make the trip

23:26.620 --> 23:28.330
from this airplane
to the hospital.

23:28.330 --> 23:32.880
[ Voice breaking ]
Frances, thank you for, um...

23:32.880 --> 23:34.790
[ Breathes sharply ]

23:34.790 --> 23:38.460
My son can't talk right now
because he had a heart attack.

23:38.460 --> 23:41.290
[ Breathes sharply ]

23:41.290 --> 23:45.830
He's only 10 years old,
but his heart stopped...

23:45.830 --> 23:47.540
[ Monitor beeping ]

23:47.540 --> 23:52.120
...because there's
not enough b-blood in his body.

23:52.120 --> 23:56.790
[ Sobs ]

23:56.790 --> 23:58.580
Frances, I know what it's like
to be paralyzed

23:58.580 --> 24:01.290
by something that hasn't
happened yet and probably won't,

24:01.290 --> 24:04.170
but it feels so true
that it's gonna end you.

24:04.170 --> 24:06.380
But what's killing this
little boy is very real,

24:06.380 --> 24:09.460
and you can fight that.
[ Sobs ]

24:09.460 --> 24:12.960
That's what you came here to do,
so let me help you do it.

24:12.960 --> 24:15.040
And you will not break.

24:15.040 --> 24:17.380
I -- I will lift you up,
and I will carry you.

24:17.380 --> 24:19.620
I served four tours in Iraq,

24:19.620 --> 24:21.500
so there's no one
better qualified

24:21.500 --> 24:22.790
to protect you, Frances,

24:22.790 --> 24:26.420
and I will, okay?

24:26.420 --> 24:27.790
I promise.

24:27.790 --> 24:31.040
[ Breathing shakily ]

24:31.040 --> 24:36.920
♪♪

24:36.920 --> 24:42.830
♪♪

24:42.830 --> 24:44.460
[ Sobs ]

24:44.460 --> 24:45.710
We're on our way.

24:45.710 --> 24:47.750
[ Gasps ]

24:47.750 --> 24:50.000
[ Voice breaking ]
Oh, baby.

24:51.710 --> 24:54.250
[ Crying ]
Thank you.

24:54.250 --> 24:55.620
[ Crying ]

24:55.620 --> 24:57.620
♪♪

24:57.620 --> 24:59.170
Oh, my!

24:59.170 --> 25:01.210
Let's go.
[ Grunts lightly ]

25:01.210 --> 25:09.380
♪♪

25:09.380 --> 25:11.290
Jo, if you didn't exist,

25:11.290 --> 25:12.920
Megan Hunt's
abdominal wall transplant

25:12.920 --> 25:15.210
would have never happened.

25:15.210 --> 25:19.460
I snaked that transplant
from an intern.

25:19.460 --> 25:23.330
Mini-livers would've taken
years, not months.

25:23.330 --> 25:27.290
Paul would still be
hurting his fiancée, I'm sure.

25:27.290 --> 25:30.750
Alex Karev would probably
still be "evilspawn."

25:30.750 --> 25:33.580
Alex Karev would not
be the man he is

25:33.580 --> 25:36.540
without loving you
or being loved by you.

25:36.540 --> 25:40.960
Violence isn't your birthright
or your inheritance.

25:40.960 --> 25:43.920
It's something
you survived

25:43.920 --> 25:47.170
because you are
the opposite of that.

25:47.170 --> 25:50.960
You have an enormous will,
an enormous heart,

25:50.960 --> 25:53.790
an enormous capacity
for survival.

25:53.790 --> 25:57.080
You've taken all this darkness
and used it to help other people

25:57.080 --> 25:59.040
who are walking
through the same.

25:59.040 --> 26:02.420
You lined that hallway
with women

26:02.420 --> 26:05.120
to help that woman
who was hurting badly

26:05.120 --> 26:07.460
just hurt
a little bit less.

26:07.460 --> 26:08.880
[ Benjamin Francis Leftwich's
"Gratitude" playing ]

26:08.880 --> 26:13.330
You've taken your darkest
experiences that life gave you,

26:13.330 --> 26:16.670
and you turned it around
and turned it into light.

26:16.670 --> 26:19.790
And if the woman who gave birth
to you doesn't want to see that,

26:19.790 --> 26:21.880
then that's on her.

26:21.880 --> 26:26.420
♪♪

26:26.420 --> 26:28.670
[ Sighs ]

26:28.670 --> 26:30.830
♪♪

26:30.830 --> 26:35.000
You know, there was a moment
years ago, I...

26:35.000 --> 26:39.120
slipped,
and I fell into the Sound.

26:39.120 --> 26:42.210
Into freezing,
freezing cold water.

26:42.210 --> 26:45.620
♪ I would not have listened,
I wouldn't have known how ♪

26:45.620 --> 26:46.830
♪ Would have burned down
all the bridges ♪

26:46.830 --> 26:49.000
And I thought to myself,
just for one moment,

26:49.000 --> 26:52.830
I thought, "Why fight?

26:52.830 --> 26:54.670
Why not just stop?"

26:54.670 --> 26:56.880
♪ So nothing could be found ♪

26:56.880 --> 26:57.710
But you fought.

26:57.710 --> 27:01.040
No, I didn't.

27:01.040 --> 27:02.540
I stopped.

27:02.540 --> 27:03.790
The only reason I'm here

27:03.790 --> 27:04.960
is because
the people who loved me

27:04.960 --> 27:06.380
didn't give up on me,

27:06.380 --> 27:09.880
so what I'm asking you is,
is this you telling me

27:09.880 --> 27:11.750
that you just need a few more
days under the covers

27:11.750 --> 27:13.750
until you can
go back to work?

27:13.750 --> 27:16.420
Or are you telling me
that you want to stop?

27:16.420 --> 27:19.540
♪ Not to waste any time
like I wasted before ♪

27:19.540 --> 27:25.290
♪ Now I know what
I'm staying for ♪

27:25.290 --> 27:29.920
♪ No more ♪

27:29.920 --> 27:31.460
I don't want to stop.

27:31.460 --> 27:34.920
♪ Now I know
what I'm praying for ♪

27:34.920 --> 27:36.790
[ Quietly ] And I do.

27:36.790 --> 27:42.580
♪ Not to waste any time
like I wasted before ♪

27:42.580 --> 27:44.670
♪ Now I know
what I'm staying for ♪

27:44.670 --> 27:48.500
Okay, so then we are going to
go talk to Bailey.

27:48.500 --> 27:50.040
We're gonna talk to Alex.

27:50.040 --> 27:51.460
[ Sniffles ]
Oh, God. I don't want to.

27:51.460 --> 27:53.170
No,
I know you don't want to.

27:53.170 --> 27:55.380
But we have to get you
the right kind of help.

27:55.380 --> 27:58.210
We have to get you
a proper leave of absence

27:58.210 --> 28:02.080
so that your career is waiting
for you when you come back.

28:02.080 --> 28:04.540
Come on, Jo.
I have you.

28:04.540 --> 28:05.750
Please.

28:05.750 --> 28:08.420
♪ Now I know
what I'm staying for ♪

28:08.420 --> 28:09.670
Come on.

28:09.670 --> 28:12.540
All you have to do
is get up and take a shower.

28:12.540 --> 28:13.790
[ Sighs ]

28:13.790 --> 28:15.620
Are you telling me
that I stink?

28:15.620 --> 28:17.380
[ Sighs ]

28:17.380 --> 28:19.750
Well, I'm not gonna
start lying to you now.

28:19.750 --> 28:21.960
[ Laughs ]

28:21.960 --> 28:23.620
[ Sniffles ]

28:23.620 --> 28:24.830
♪♪

28:24.830 --> 28:27.290
[ Quietly ] Okay. Okay.

28:33.330 --> 28:34.920
[ Horns honk ]

28:34.920 --> 28:38.170
♪ We'll stay home instead ♪

28:38.170 --> 28:40.000
♪ Boom, boom, boom, boom ♪

28:40.000 --> 28:41.330
Driver:
Damn this traffic.

28:41.330 --> 28:42.790
♪ Yeah, yeah, yeah ♪
And now we've
got fog rolling in.

28:42.790 --> 28:44.250
Should we come off here?

28:44.250 --> 28:45.880
I mean, would Mercer be
any faster or...

28:45.880 --> 28:47.290
[ Chuckles ]
Funny.

28:47.290 --> 28:50.290
♪ Wake me up
before you go-go ♪

28:50.290 --> 28:53.290
♪ 'Cause I'm not planning
on going solo ♪

28:53.290 --> 28:56.170
Both: ♪ Wake me up
before you go-go ♪

28:56.170 --> 29:00.290
♪ I don't want to miss it
when you hit that hiiiigh ♪

29:00.290 --> 29:02.710
[ Horns honking ]

29:02.710 --> 29:03.880
Woman on PA: Dr. Kroner
to Nurses' Station 2.

29:03.880 --> 29:05.290
Alex: All right,
call me with any updates.

29:05.290 --> 29:06.580
Bye.
Dr. Kroner
to Nurses' Station 2.

29:06.580 --> 29:08.710
They're on the highway,
but they're stuck in traffic.

29:08.710 --> 29:11.580
Oh, my God.
Can anything go our way, please?

29:11.580 --> 29:13.750
His hemoglobin is 3.1.

29:13.750 --> 29:15.040
He has oxygen debt.

29:15.040 --> 29:16.790
What --
What does that mean?

29:16.790 --> 29:18.580
It means if we don't get oxygen
to his organs somehow,

29:18.580 --> 29:20.420
they could
continue to fail.

29:20.420 --> 29:23.380
You told me
you would find the blood.

29:23.380 --> 29:25.620
You told me
you would fix him.

29:25.620 --> 29:28.210
You told me
you wouldn't give up!

29:28.210 --> 29:31.620
♪♪

29:31.620 --> 29:33.540
Hyperbaric chamber.

29:33.540 --> 29:34.920
Altman, wait.

29:34.920 --> 29:36.330
Get a gurney.

29:36.330 --> 29:37.500
Hyperbaric chamber.

29:37.500 --> 29:38.880
What's that?

29:38.880 --> 29:40.380
It's an oxygen-rich
environment.

29:40.380 --> 29:42.210
It allows more oxygen
to get to his organs.

29:42.210 --> 29:43.750
It could buy us some time,
right?

29:43.750 --> 29:46.170
Yes.
Do it. Do it.

29:46.170 --> 29:47.460
Dr. Altman!

29:47.460 --> 29:48.750
It's Kari Donnelly.

29:48.750 --> 29:50.040
Her CT is back.
It's bad.

29:50.040 --> 29:51.420
You got this?
Yeah.

29:51.420 --> 29:52.420
Okay.

29:52.420 --> 29:54.170
All right, let's go.

29:54.170 --> 29:55.880
♪♪

29:55.880 --> 29:56.620
[ Birds chirping ]

29:56.620 --> 29:57.880
Jackson: Okay.

29:57.880 --> 29:59.330
Maggie: Ow. Ow, ow!

29:59.330 --> 30:00.580
-I know.
-Ow!

30:00.580 --> 30:01.790
I got an ice pack
for you in the tent

30:01.790 --> 30:03.380
and some ointment.

30:03.380 --> 30:04.960
Bugs find me.

30:04.960 --> 30:06.540
You know, they just --

30:06.540 --> 30:08.290
they smell my fear,
and they target me.

30:08.290 --> 30:09.380
Aah.
Okay.

30:09.380 --> 30:10.750
You know it's genetic?

30:10.750 --> 30:11.920
Did you know that?

30:11.920 --> 30:13.420
That there are actually
genetic markers

30:13.420 --> 30:15.460
that determine whether
a bug likes to bite you?

30:15.460 --> 30:18.500
I have those markers,
which, you know,

30:18.500 --> 30:21.920
I mean, maybe we just
chalk this up to genetics.

30:21.920 --> 30:23.330
All right.
Well, I'm gonna...
[ Bag unzips ]

30:23.330 --> 30:25.880
...look up the insects
in this area on my phone.

30:25.880 --> 30:27.540
I mean, maybe we --
we just --

30:27.540 --> 30:29.830
we let it be okay that
I am who I am, and...

30:29.830 --> 30:30.920
Ah!
All right, all right.

30:30.920 --> 30:32.210
...you are
who you are?

30:32.210 --> 30:34.790
And, um, maybe we don't --

30:34.790 --> 30:37.330
we don't need to -- to try to
like what the other likes?

30:37.330 --> 30:40.380
[ Sighs ] Okay.

30:40.380 --> 30:42.210
You know, because
I like crossword puzzles,

30:42.210 --> 30:43.960
and I would never force you
to do a crossword puzzle

30:43.960 --> 30:45.250
because
you would hate that.

30:45.250 --> 30:47.380
Maggie, you need to, uh --
you need to call the hospital.

30:47.380 --> 30:48.670
I thought
we were unplugging.

30:48.670 --> 30:49.540
Maggie.

30:49.540 --> 30:51.210
♪♪

30:51.210 --> 30:52.540
Oh, my God.
Gus.

30:52.540 --> 30:54.670
We have to go.

30:54.670 --> 30:56.670
Yep. I'm on it.

30:56.670 --> 30:58.120
[ Sighs ]

30:58.120 --> 31:02.210
♪♪

31:06.380 --> 31:08.710
Kari, your CT came back,

31:08.710 --> 31:10.710
and it shows that
you have a cavitary lesion,

31:10.710 --> 31:13.540
which I think is the source
of your infection.

31:13.540 --> 31:15.880
But I'm sorry -- we are gonna
have to go in surgically

31:15.880 --> 31:18.580
and remove one of the lobes
of your lung.

31:18.580 --> 31:19.880
Is that safe?

31:19.880 --> 31:21.620
Sh-Shouldn't we wait to see
if the stem cells worked?

31:21.620 --> 31:23.250
If we wait,
she could get septic.

31:23.250 --> 31:24.880
So we're screwed
either way.

31:24.880 --> 31:27.250
Toby. Honey.

31:27.250 --> 31:29.830
There's no living
without risk.

31:29.830 --> 31:32.210
You know that
better than I do.

31:32.210 --> 31:34.290
Up until two years ago,

31:34.290 --> 31:36.500
I had that boring job
I hated so much

31:36.500 --> 31:38.920
I'd cry in my car
every day at lunch,

31:38.920 --> 31:40.880
but I was too scared
to quit.

31:40.880 --> 31:44.000
And then you came home
and you said,

31:44.000 --> 31:47.120
"Mom, I'm not a woman.

31:47.120 --> 31:49.710
And I'm not a man.

31:49.710 --> 31:52.380
I'm both.

31:52.380 --> 31:55.920
And I love you, but I don't care
if you like it or not."

31:55.920 --> 31:59.460
And I realized how much of
my life I've lived in fear

31:59.460 --> 32:03.120
while you, my child,
who I made,

32:03.120 --> 32:05.580
was living your truest,
most authentic life.

32:05.580 --> 32:10.120
Your bravery is the reason
I started really living,

32:10.120 --> 32:12.120
and not once
in these last two weeks

32:12.120 --> 32:13.580
have I missed
that safe life.

32:13.580 --> 32:15.080
Not once.

32:15.080 --> 32:20.210
I got to live
because of you, Toby.

32:20.210 --> 32:21.380
Because you taught me

32:21.380 --> 32:23.500
that we have to
throw ourselves in, right?

32:23.500 --> 32:26.500
All in.

32:26.500 --> 32:28.540
All in.

32:28.540 --> 32:30.790
[ Crying ] Okay, then.

32:30.790 --> 32:33.330
[ Sniffles ]

32:33.330 --> 32:34.750
Let's do the surgery.

32:34.750 --> 32:36.670
Okay.

32:36.670 --> 32:39.210
All in.

32:39.210 --> 32:42.670
[ Sighs ] Altman took Kari in
for a lobectomy.

32:42.670 --> 32:46.960
Of course she did because
this is just one of those days.

32:46.960 --> 32:49.210
I would stay,
but Leo, uh, has a cold

32:49.210 --> 32:51.080
and Owen is on
some rescue mission,

32:51.080 --> 32:52.750
so I'm gonna
take him home.

32:52.750 --> 32:53.830
Home?

32:53.830 --> 32:55.080
Yeah.
To Owen's house.

32:55.080 --> 32:58.120
[ Leo coughs, babbles ]

32:58.120 --> 33:00.830
Is this your past
or your future?

33:00.830 --> 33:02.120
[ Leo babbling ]

33:02.120 --> 33:04.460
What?
Owen and Leo.

33:04.460 --> 33:06.040
Because I was okay
with the whole

33:06.040 --> 33:08.750
"This isn't a real thing, it's
just pain management" scenario

33:08.750 --> 33:12.170
right up until this started to
feel like a real thing for me.

33:12.170 --> 33:14.580
But you hide me
from your family.

33:14.580 --> 33:16.460
You're still playing house
with Owen.

33:16.460 --> 33:19.250
So I'm saying,
what do you want?

33:19.250 --> 33:20.750
Is this real for you,
too?

33:20.750 --> 33:23.040
'Cause if not,
I need to know.

33:23.040 --> 33:27.500
Like right this minute while
I'm taking care of a sick baby?

33:27.500 --> 33:31.420
I don't just...expect the best
out of life, Amelia.

33:31.420 --> 33:33.120
I-I do what I can
to help the best come along,

33:33.120 --> 33:34.670
so I'm not inclined
to hang around in a situation

33:34.670 --> 33:36.500
which I know will
for sure end in pain

33:36.500 --> 33:37.670
because I've --
I've had enough pain.

33:37.670 --> 33:39.210
So, no.

33:39.210 --> 33:43.460
[ Sigh ] Not this minute,
but soon.

33:43.460 --> 33:46.250
I'll keep you posted
on Kari.

33:46.250 --> 33:47.710
[ Indistinct conversations ]

33:47.710 --> 33:49.080
[ Telephone ringing
in distance ]

33:49.080 --> 33:51.120
[ Whispering ] So, anyway,

33:51.120 --> 33:52.330
let's just see
where she is, okay?

33:52.330 --> 33:53.620
Hey.
Hey.

33:53.620 --> 33:56.380
I need to talk to Bailey.
I would not do that.

33:56.380 --> 33:57.830
They've been in there all day
dealing with some kind of --

33:57.830 --> 33:59.500
[ Singsong voice ] Drama.

33:59.500 --> 34:01.380
Meredith: Okay, well,
whatever drama it is can wait.

34:01.380 --> 34:02.420
I need to speak to her.

34:02.420 --> 34:04.000
No, no, no.
I-I can wait.

34:04.000 --> 34:07.080
I can wait until she's done,
and then I can fill her in.

34:07.080 --> 34:10.000
If you talk to Alex,
I'll talk to Bailey.

34:11.710 --> 34:14.080
Andrew, can you, uh,
stay with Jo, please?

34:14.080 --> 34:15.580
Yeah, of course.

34:15.580 --> 34:17.290
Okay. Don't leave her side.
It's important.

34:17.290 --> 34:18.920
Okay.

34:18.920 --> 34:20.960
Woman on PA:
Dr. Angemi, extension 2107.

34:20.960 --> 34:23.750
Dr. Angemi, extension 2107.

34:23.750 --> 34:25.580
Do you love her?

34:25.580 --> 34:27.420
She told you?

34:27.420 --> 34:28.750
Do you?

34:28.750 --> 34:31.460
Who wouldn't?

34:31.460 --> 34:33.330
[ Cellphone chimes, vibrates ]

34:33.330 --> 34:35.710
Oh, what's that?

34:35.710 --> 34:38.500
Bailey.

34:38.500 --> 34:40.170
You should go in there.

34:40.170 --> 34:41.880
I -- No. No, no.

34:41.880 --> 34:43.040
Meredith said to stay with you.
I mean --

34:43.040 --> 34:44.460
No, I'm fine.
I can wait here.

34:44.460 --> 34:45.710
Dude,
what did you do?

34:45.710 --> 34:46.960
I don't know!

34:46.960 --> 34:48.750
Go. Go!

34:48.750 --> 34:50.830
[ Sighs ]

34:50.830 --> 34:53.620
Close the door and have a seat,
please, Dr. DeLuca.

34:53.620 --> 34:55.080
[ Door creaks lightly ]

34:55.080 --> 34:58.500
[ Sighs ]
Um, on the 2nd of this month,

34:58.500 --> 34:59.620
you worked in the clinic.

34:59.620 --> 35:00.620
Is that correct?

35:00.620 --> 35:02.710
Um, I'd have to check,
but, yeah.

35:02.710 --> 35:03.960
I'm sure
your records are right.

35:03.960 --> 35:06.830
Okay. And on that day,

35:06.830 --> 35:09.080
you treated
one Gabriella Rivera?

35:09.080 --> 35:13.330
♪♪

35:13.330 --> 35:15.460
Yes, we resected
a part of her colon

35:15.460 --> 35:17.460
and diagnosed her with
non-Hodgkin's lymphoma.

35:17.460 --> 35:19.120
Who is "we"?

35:19.120 --> 35:21.420
♪♪

35:21.420 --> 35:23.210
I-I'm sorry.
W-What is this all about?

35:23.210 --> 35:26.000
Dr. DeLuca,
these people are inspectors

35:26.000 --> 35:28.620
from the
Olympia United Medical Group.

35:28.620 --> 35:30.250
They provide
your insurance

35:30.250 --> 35:34.170
and that of every employee
at Grey-Sloan Memorial.

35:34.170 --> 35:36.880
It has come to light
that Dr. Meredith Grey

35:36.880 --> 35:39.380
submitted
her own daughter's name

35:39.380 --> 35:41.790
to pay for Gabriella's
surgery and care,

35:41.790 --> 35:45.460
which is both a fraud
and a felony.

35:45.460 --> 35:50.120
So we're going to need you to be
a lot more specific.

35:57.750 --> 36:00.000
She's more at risk
to get a post-op fever,

36:00.000 --> 36:01.250
so you need to
keep a close eye on her.

36:01.250 --> 36:03.000
Well, hello there.
Hey.

36:03.000 --> 36:04.380
I've just used these
million-dollar hands

36:04.380 --> 36:07.080
on a nasty
fusiform aneurysm,

36:07.080 --> 36:08.750
and guess what
they're tackling next --

36:08.750 --> 36:10.330
an IKEA changing table,

36:10.330 --> 36:12.670
which I believe is called
a "FLURRD."

36:12.670 --> 36:14.380
You heading home,
or you got to, uh, hang around

36:14.380 --> 36:15.580
for the golden blood?

36:15.580 --> 36:17.170
Uh, no.
Gus can't have surgery.

36:17.170 --> 36:18.880
He can only handle a transfusion
right now.

36:18.880 --> 36:20.960
[ Sighs ]

36:22.670 --> 36:24.920
Are you okay?

36:26.250 --> 36:27.290
Yeah, I -- No.

36:27.290 --> 36:28.830
I -- Um, I just --

36:28.830 --> 36:30.710
Tom, I have to, um --

36:30.710 --> 36:33.670
I, uh, I have to go, uh,
take care of something.

36:33.670 --> 36:35.330
No big. I'll, uh -- I'll meet
you back at the ranch.

36:35.330 --> 36:37.670
I'll grab some dinner.
We can eat off the FLURRD.

36:37.670 --> 36:38.960
[ Chuckles ]

36:38.960 --> 36:39.830
[ Wildwood Kin's "Hold On"
plays ]

36:39.830 --> 36:43.420
♪ Hold on ♪

36:43.420 --> 36:46.170
♪♪

36:46.170 --> 36:48.880
♪ To your lights at night ♪

36:48.880 --> 36:50.790
Hey.
What happened?

36:50.790 --> 36:52.210
Oh, hemoglobin's worse,

36:52.210 --> 36:54.040
and he's starting to have
some end-organ failure.

36:54.040 --> 36:55.170
Golden blood's
stuck in traffic.

36:55.170 --> 36:56.170
Hyperbaric therapy's
our last hope.

36:56.170 --> 36:57.170
Why are you here?

36:57.170 --> 36:58.920
I-I brought Jo back.
Is she okay?

36:58.920 --> 37:00.420
She's fine,
but we should talk.

37:00.420 --> 37:01.710
We're ready, Dr. Karev.

37:01.710 --> 37:02.790
Okay. I'll --
I'll come in with you.

37:02.790 --> 37:04.080
All right.

37:05.620 --> 37:10.420
♪ Oh oh oh oh ♪

37:10.420 --> 37:14.830
♪♪

37:14.830 --> 37:15.830
[ Knock on door ]

37:15.830 --> 37:17.290
♪♪

37:17.290 --> 37:18.540
Teddy. Hi.

37:18.540 --> 37:21.540
I'm sorry. I -- I --

37:21.540 --> 37:23.330
Did I --
Did I just open a time portal?

37:23.330 --> 37:24.960
No. No, sorry.

37:24.960 --> 37:27.000
I'm, uh --
Leo has a cold.

37:27.000 --> 37:28.500
Owen is still
out in the --

37:28.500 --> 37:30.000
Are you two
back together again?

37:30.000 --> 37:32.120
'Cause if you are, I do not want
to go down that road again,

37:32.120 --> 37:33.210
so I just --
No. No, no.

37:33.210 --> 37:34.790
I'm with Leo.
I'm just here with Leo.

37:34.790 --> 37:36.580
Auntie Amelia.

37:36.580 --> 37:38.380
Uh, come in.
We're making a bottle.

37:38.380 --> 37:39.580
Okay.

37:39.580 --> 37:41.080
♪♪

37:41.080 --> 37:43.210
So, just out of curiosity,

37:43.210 --> 37:45.330
what, uh, road
are you going down?

37:45.330 --> 37:47.000
Uh, uh...

37:47.000 --> 37:49.380
[ Leo coos ]

37:49.380 --> 37:51.920
I love Owen,
and it's scary,

37:51.920 --> 37:56.080
and we hurt each other,
and it is not easy.

37:56.080 --> 37:58.380
Uh, all things I know.

37:58.380 --> 37:59.750
But I don't --
I don't want safe.

37:59.750 --> 38:03.540
I-I don't want to raise
my daughter just to feel safe.

38:03.540 --> 38:05.330
I want her to live,

38:05.330 --> 38:08.420
and I want her to have love
and see love,

38:08.420 --> 38:10.670
and Tom Koracick --
he makes me --

38:10.670 --> 38:13.460
he makes me laugh
and -- and feel safe.

38:13.460 --> 38:19.080
But I don't feel passion
or rage or ecstasy.

38:19.080 --> 38:21.000
I mean,
Owen is the only person

38:21.000 --> 38:24.250
who ever makes me feel
any of those things.

38:24.250 --> 38:26.540
Wait, really?
The only one?

38:26.540 --> 38:28.250
Yes.

38:28.250 --> 38:31.250
Owen is the only person
who has ever done that for me,

38:31.250 --> 38:33.000
and it's maddening,
and I have to tell him,

38:33.000 --> 38:35.250
and I have to tell him
before my daughter is born.

38:35.250 --> 38:38.170
Uh, you are aware
that you are leaking.

38:38.170 --> 38:40.750
Yeah, my water broke
back around "Auntie Amelia,"

38:40.750 --> 38:42.710
but I just had to say all that
before I go into labor.

38:42.710 --> 38:44.170
Uh, should we...
Yeah, we probably should.

38:44.170 --> 38:47.040
-Okay. Uh.
-Ohh.

38:47.040 --> 38:50.210
[ Cellphone ringing ]

38:53.420 --> 38:54.880
Oh, my God.

38:54.880 --> 38:55.920
[ Breathing sharply ]

38:55.920 --> 38:58.080
Teddy's water just broke.

38:58.080 --> 39:01.080
So she won't be able to
cover my service anymore.

39:01.080 --> 39:02.750
You know what?
Let's just go. Let's just go.

39:02.750 --> 39:04.330
All right, we can come back
for this stuff.

39:04.330 --> 39:06.080
I'll come back
for this stuff later.

39:06.080 --> 39:08.250
[ Thunder rumbles ]

39:08.250 --> 39:10.420
[ Rain falling ]

39:10.420 --> 39:17.380
♪♪

39:17.380 --> 39:19.920
I guess God's water
just broke, too.

39:19.920 --> 39:21.330
[ Thunder crashes ]

39:21.330 --> 39:22.500
Meredith: There will be
no shortage of times

39:22.500 --> 39:24.920
when you feel like giving up.

39:24.920 --> 39:28.170
But you can't let that fear
or desperation stop you.

39:28.170 --> 39:30.790
Pressure's at 2.4 ATA,
so we're stuck in here.

39:30.790 --> 39:32.620
Is he still
having ST changes?

39:32.620 --> 39:33.960
Uh, nothing's
resolved yet.

39:33.960 --> 39:36.380
We should know soon
if it's working.

39:36.380 --> 39:38.750
[ Sighs ] What the hell
happened with Jo?

39:38.750 --> 39:40.000
Did she talk to you?
Did she tell you anything?

39:40.000 --> 39:41.380
DeLuca: Dr. Grey?

39:41.380 --> 39:43.120
Hey, it's not a good time
right now.

39:43.120 --> 39:45.170
This can't wait.

39:45.170 --> 39:47.620
What happened?
Where's Jo?

39:47.620 --> 39:51.880
Your patient, Gabby Rivera --
I, uh -- I lied to you.

39:51.880 --> 39:52.880
What?

39:52.880 --> 39:54.210
She didn't have insurance,

39:54.210 --> 39:55.580
and she shouldn't
have been admitted,

39:55.580 --> 40:00.880
but I wanted her to
get the surgery very badly.

40:00.880 --> 40:02.710
And so,
I didn't tell anyone,

40:02.710 --> 40:05.080
and I put another name down
on her paperwork.

40:05.080 --> 40:07.040
♪♪

40:07.040 --> 40:08.920
Your daughter's name,
Ellis.

40:08.920 --> 40:10.120
And I'm so sorry.

40:10.120 --> 40:11.170
Andrew, no.

40:11.170 --> 40:13.540
It's all been cleared up.

40:13.540 --> 40:15.420
I got caught.

40:15.420 --> 40:18.460
I just spoke
with Chief Bailey and Dr. Fox.

40:18.460 --> 40:20.670
I wanted to apologize
to you first

40:20.670 --> 40:22.290
before going to the police
to let you know what I'd done.

40:22.290 --> 40:23.790
No. Andrew,
do not do that.

40:23.790 --> 40:26.290
It's not fair to you,
and it's not fair to your kids.

40:26.290 --> 40:28.250
Who need you.

40:28.250 --> 40:31.540
I committed a felony,
and I'll likely go to jail.

40:31.540 --> 40:32.750
♪♪

40:32.750 --> 40:35.790
I'm sorry
I put you all at risk.

40:35.790 --> 40:37.330
Andrew.
No, Andrew. Don't.

40:37.330 --> 40:40.540
Andrew,
do not go to the police!

40:40.540 --> 40:42.040
Do not!

40:42.040 --> 40:44.170
Andrew.

40:44.170 --> 40:46.580
Andrew!

40:46.580 --> 40:47.670
Andrew!

40:47.670 --> 40:49.830
Even when you feel trapped.

40:49.830 --> 40:52.000
Even when it feels like
there is no end in sight.

40:52.000 --> 40:54.040
Levi: Is it possible
we're going slower?

40:54.040 --> 40:55.880
Can we pick it up, please?
This is an emergency.

40:55.880 --> 40:57.710
Sorry, but if you can see better
through this fog,

40:57.710 --> 41:00.170
you should drive.

41:00.170 --> 41:02.290
Oh, my God.
[ Breathing deeply ]

41:02.290 --> 41:04.210
I've never seen it
like this.

41:04.210 --> 41:05.420
Close the window,
Schmitt.

41:05.420 --> 41:07.170
Do you mind
keeping it open?

41:07.170 --> 41:09.330
It reminds me of home.

41:09.330 --> 41:12.580
Mornings in autumn
when the fog comes in.

41:12.580 --> 41:16.380
Feels like everything's
cushioned, softer.

41:16.380 --> 41:18.540
The world feels safer.

41:18.540 --> 41:21.380
Even when things are moving
faster than you can comprehend.

41:21.380 --> 41:22.420
It's actually my favorite.
[ Tires screech ]

41:22.420 --> 41:24.210
[ Crashing ]
What the hell was that?

41:24.210 --> 41:25.620
Oh, my God!
Oh, my God!
[ Screams ]

41:25.620 --> 41:27.290
[ Whimpering ]
They can't see.

41:27.290 --> 41:28.380
They don't know to stop.
They can't see!

41:28.380 --> 41:29.420
No, wait!
Don't get out!

41:29.420 --> 41:30.420
[ Horn honks, tires screech ]

41:30.420 --> 41:31.790
[ Crash, horns blare ]

41:31.790 --> 41:34.000
Even when every part of you
is certain...

41:34.000 --> 41:35.620
[ Screaming ]

41:35.620 --> 41:37.500
...that all...
It's okay.

41:37.500 --> 41:40.290
[ Screaming ]
...is lost.

41:48.500 --> 41:58.000
♪♪

41:58.000 --> 42:07.580
♪♪

42:07.580 --> 42:16.880
♪♪
